<author><name><![CDATA[tepples]]></name></author>
<updated>2019-01-09T14:10:01-07:00</updated>
<published>2019-01-09T14:10:01-07:00</published>
<id>http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=18293&amp;p=231831#p231831</id>
<link href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=18293&amp;p=231831#p231831"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[NES Graphics • Re: When did sprite black outlines became standard ?]]></title>

<category term="NES Graphics" scheme="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewforum.php?f=21" label="NES Graphics"/>
<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=18293&amp;p=231831#p231831"><![CDATA[
GBC had the same limit on colors per sprite as the NES: 3 per 8x8 or 8x16 pixel tile. But I'll admit GBC had less pressure from overdraw (50% vs. 25%) and unique sprite palettes (8 vs. 4), allowing more games to adopt <em>Mega Man</em>/<em>SMB2</em>-style overlays for their sprites. GBA, on the other hand, had to contend with an excessively dark display as well as skilled staff being reassigned to games for sixth gen consoles (PS2, GameCube, and Xbox).<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=9">tepples</a> — Wed Jan 09, 2019 2:10 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
